{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Rows with missing required fields are rejected and appear in the dead-letter queue with the original row number.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is between CSV parsing (row indexing), schema validation, and DLQ routing. A unit test of validator logic can pass while integration wiring still drops/offsets row numbers or misroutes rejected rows.","test_description":"Run the row-processing pipeline end-to-end in-process with a real CSV parser and schema validator, using a test DLQ sink (e.g., local table/file/queue adapter). Feed a CSV containing missing required fields at known line numbers and assert each rejected record appears in DLQ with the exact original row number and rejection reason.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The transformation correctly converts date strings in multiple formats (ISO 8601, US, European) to a single canonical format.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Date normalization is a deterministic transformation with no required I/O. Real failures are most directly caught at the pure function boundary using representative inputs and edge cases.","test_description":"Table-driven test for the date normalization function with ISO 8601, US (MM/DD/YYYY), and European (DD/MM/YYYY) inputs, including ambiguous and invalid dates. Assert canonical output format and explicit error handling for unparseable inputs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A CSV file with 500,000 rows completes processing within the configured timeout without running out of memory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a resource/throughput guarantee tied to real process memory, runtime,